{{Infobox military installation | name = | ensign = | ensign_size = | native_name = | partof = <!-- for elements within a larger site --> | location = [[Gettysburg National Military Park]], [[Adams County, Pennsylvania]] | nearest_town = <!-- used in military test site infobox --> | country = [[United States]] | image = | alt = | caption = | image2 = <!--secondary image, major command emblems for airfields --> | alt2 = | caption2 = | type = | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord}} --> | gridref = | image_map = 1913 Gettysburg reunion map.png | image_mapsize = | image_map_alt = | image_map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_alt = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_relief = | pushpin_image = | pushpin_label = | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_mark = | pushpin_marksize = | ownership = [[United States Department of War]] | operator = <!-- where different from ownership such as the RAF or the USAF --> | controlledby = <!-- such as RAF Bomber Command or the Eighth Air Force --> | open_to_public = <!-- for out of use sites/sites with museums etc --> | site_other_label = <!-- for renaming "Other facilities" in infobox --> | site_other = <!-- for other sorts of facilities - radar types etc --> | site_area = <!-- area of site m2, km2 square mile etc --> | code = <!--facility/installation code, applies to US --> | built = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY}} --> | used = <!--{{End date|1946}} --> | builder = | materials = | height = <!-- height of tallest part, not above sea level --> | length = <!-- for border fences or other DMZs --> | fate = <!--changed from demolished parameter--> | condition = | battles = | events = | current_commander = <!-- current commander --> | past_commanders = <!-- past notable commander(s) --> | garrison = <!-- such as the 25th Bombardment Group --> | occupants = <!-- squadrons only --> | website = | footnotes = <!-- catchall in case it's needed to preserve something in infobox that doesn't work in new code --> }} The '''1913 Gettysburg reunion''' was a [[Gettysburg Battlefield]] [[Gettysburg Battlefield camps after the American Civil War|encampment]] of [[American Civil War]] veterans for the [[Battle of Gettysburg]]'s 50th anniversary. The June 29–July 4 gathering of 53,407 veterans (~8,750 Confederate)<ref name=Beitler/><!--{{Rp|40,222,228}}--> was the largest ever Civil War veteran reunion, and "''never before in the world's history ''[had]'' so great a number of men so advanced in years been assembled under field conditions''" (Chief Surgeon).<ref name=Bradley>{{Cite report |last=Bradley |first=A. E. (Lieut. Colonel) |date=October 24, 1913 |title=Office of Chief Surgeon Report |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=swkTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA43 |format=Google Books |work=Report of the Pennsylvania Commission |publisher=Medical Corps, U. S. Army |accessdate=2011-02-06 |quote=''The youngest veteran known to have been at the camp was 61 years of age. The oldest alleged that he was 112 years.''}} (p. 60)</ref>{{Rp|60}} All honorably discharged veterans in the [[Grand Army of the Republic]] and the [[United Confederate Veterans]] were invited, and veterans from 46 of the 48 states attended<ref>{{cite book |last=Davis |first=William C. |year=1995|edition=Fifth Printing |origyear=1983 |title=Gettysburg: The Story Behind the Scenery |lccn=83080606 |isbn=0-916122-89-1 |page=28 |quote=''Pennsylvanians made up the bulk of them: 22,103 to be exact, 303 of whom were Confederate veterans. Yet men came from all but 2 of the 48 states.''}}</ref> ([[cf.]] Nevada and Wyoming).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://segtours.com/blog/archives/1989 |title=Attendance Figures for 1913 and 1938 Gettysburg Reunions |publisher=Segway Tours of Gettysburg Blog |accessdate=2018-07-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gettysburgcompiler.org/tag/50th-anniversary/ |title=Pennsylvania College During the 50th Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg |last=Tapscott |first=Logan |publisher=The Gettysburg Compiler |date=2011-11-17 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309192838/https://gettysburgcompiler.org/tag/50th-anniversary/ |archivedate=2018-03-09 |accessdate=2018-07-19 }}</ref> Despite concerns "that there might be unpleasant differences, at least, between the blue and gray"<ref>{{Cite news |date=April 18, 1914 |title=The Peace Memorial Bill: Speech of Colonel Andrew Cowan of Louisville |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kdElAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yfQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=7214,4563599&dq=andrew-cowan+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archive |newspaper=Gettysburg Compiler |accessdate=2011-02-02}}</ref> (as after England's [[War of the Roses]] and the [[French Revolution]]),<ref>{{Cite news |date=March 29, 1913 |title=The Gettysburg Reunion |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=swkTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA187 |format=Google Books |work=Report of the Pennsylvania Commission |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref> the peaceful reunion was repeatedly marked by events of Union–Confederate camaraderie.<ref name=Pittsburgh/> President [[Woodrow Wilson]]'s July 4 reunion address summarized the spirit: "''We have found one another again as brothers and comrades in arms, enemies no longer, generous friends rather, our battles long past, the quarrel forgotten—except that we shall not forget the splendid valor.''"
{{External media |image1=[http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/h?ammem/gmd:@field(NUMBER+@band(g3822g+cw0351300)) 1913 GNPC map for reunion] }}
==Planning== After numerous smaller Gettysburg reunions, including the 1906 [[Philadelphia Brigade]]/[[Pickett's Charge|Pickett's Division]] reunion during which Brig. Gen. [[Lewis Armistead]]'s captured sword was returned to the South,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Frazier |first=John W |year=1906 |title=Reunion of the Blue and Gray: Philadelphia Brigade and Pickett's Division |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QeNYAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA10 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=Ware Bros, Company, Printers |format=Google Books |accessdate=2011-02-06}}</ref> in April 1908 General [[Henry S. Huidekoper]] of Philadelphia suggested a 1913 50th anniversary reunion to Pennsylvania Governor [[Edwin Sydney Stuart]].<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|178}} On September 8,<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'13}} the [[Gettysburg National Military Park|Gettysburg National Park Commission]]<!--Nicholson--> met with Gettysburg borough officials about the event, Stuart conducted a sub-committee meeting on October 25, and Stuart addressed the General Assembly in January 1909.<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|178}}
On May 13, 1909, the Pennsylvania Assembly created the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg Commission,<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 30, 1913 |title=Civil War Veterans To Meet On Gettysburg Battlefield |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=UV5XAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Y0QNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4154,1356157&dq=1909+regulars+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archive |newspaper=The Hudson Independent |accessdate=2011-06-09}}</ref> and the commission's "first tentative programme"<!--perhaps p. 167--> of October 13, 1910<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'13}} included a "Peace Jubilee"<!--pp. xx, 230--> with noon July 3 placement of the cornerstone for a<!--p. 166--> "[[Eternal Light Peace Memorial|Great Peace Memorial]]".<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|173}} The August 26, 1912, US Congress bill appropriated $150K and directed the [[United States Department of War|War Department]] establish the camp,<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|181}} but the memorial funding was not approved and the "Peace Jubilee" plans were removed from the schedule. The site for the camp and the {{convert|8|acre}} for the Great Tent west of the Codori House were selected in 1912 and mapped by the Gettysburg National Park Commission.<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} The Park Commission also completed painting of avenue fencing, gun carriages, iron tablets, pyramids, and shells from 1912 through June 30, 1913.<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} On April 13, 1913, the Pennsylvania commission completed [[the Pennsylvania State Memorial]]<ref name=Loski>{{Cite web|last=Loski |first=Diana |title=The Pennsylvania Memorial: A Centennial |url=http://www.thegettysburgexperience.com/past_issue_headlines/2010/september2010/pamemorial.html |publisher=GettysburgExperience.com |accessdate=2011-02-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128200959/https://thegettysburgexperience.com/past_issue_headlines/2010/september2010/pamemorial.html |archivedate=2010-11-28 |df= }}</ref> and also mailed 40,000 veteran's invitations.<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|22}} On June 28, President [[Woodrow Wilson]] notified the Pennsylvania commission he would attend the reunion for a "very limited period".<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|173}} The 33 contributing states provided a total of $1,033,000 for the reunion ($450,000 from Pennsylvania).<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|228}}
The Pennsylvania commission headquarters at Gettysburg was at [https://www.google.com/#sclient=psy&hl=en&site=&source=hp&q=231+baltimore+st+gettysburg+pa 231 Baltimore St,]<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|22}} with the Harrisburg office of the Secretary (later nicknamed the "Duke of Gettysburg")<ref name=July2>{{Cite news |date=July 2, 1913 |title=50th Anniversary Is Here & Toll Free to Gettysburg |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=9qGwjJavaBUC&dat=19130702&printsec=frontpage |format=Google News |newspaper=Gettysburg Compiler |accessdate=2011-02-07}} ([http://www.gdg.org/Research/Other%20Documents/50th%20Anniversary.doc GDG.org Microsoft Word version,] [https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:ptN3tD3woRUJ:www.gdg.org/Research/Other%2520Documents/50th%2520Anniversary.doc+%22Gettysburg+Jubilee%22&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESjII2VAy8RGOq1gbioa-1JppRvNUIFt7XZpipIPCpCP8JtbCxTmj1DMeO0ZMUITd5fObw3FsKVBuASEmjkPgKf5D4Th2SWDf0OdtJgJG833Gx4jAdp44cn2UT3slzltWDzdWQjT&sig=AHIEtbRxQKfnusV-g48LIf4ISMOvyEmhngGoogle Quick View version)]</ref> in [[Pennsylvania State Capitol]] Room 509.<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|26}}--> Various commemorative tokens and programs were developed for attendees, including 3 types of Pennsylvania badges ("PRESS", "GUEST", "SCOUT"),<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|160}}--> a commemorative medal,<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|236}}--><ref name=Feb8/>{{Rp|8}} and a souvenir program of poems by the attending "Veteran Scout", [[John Wallace Crawford|Jack Crawford]].<ref name=Crawford>{{Citation |last=Crawford |first=John Wallace "Jack" |year=1913 |title=A Prayer and a Benediction … and Other Poems from his new book |url=http://www.cowanauctions.com/peek-in-warehouse/item.aspx?ItemId=82766 |format=listing, Cowan's Auctions |accessdate=2011-02-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708195948/http://www.cowanauctions.com/peek-in-warehouse/item.aspx?ItemId=82766 |archive-date=2011-07-08 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><!--name=Beitler>{{Rp|58b photo}}--> The [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] Company also added "a telephone line between Gettysburg and Hanover along the [[Western Maryland Railway]], over which the Pennsy [would] operate a large number of trains during the battle anniversary".<ref name=June28/>{{Rp|1}} On the [[Chambersburg, Pennsylvania|Chambersburg]]-Gettysburg turnpike and the Gettysburg-[[Littlestown, Pennsylvania|Petersburg]] turnpike, tolls ended in time for the reunion when on June 27, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the 1911 Sproul Roads Act, by which the Commonwealth acquired private toll roads.<ref name=July2/>{{Rp|1}}
By February 1, 1913, water wells were being drilled for the July encampment,<ref name=Feb8>{{Cite news |date=February 8, 1913 |title=Railroad Blocks Trolley Plans" & "Medals for the Gettysburg Men |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5DdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YjoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7010,1049478&dq=trolley+round-top&hl=en |format=Google News Archives |newspaper=Adams County News |accessdate=2011-01-22}} ([https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=W6RcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZVgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2708,5385858&dq=pen-mar-racing-circuit&hl=en Gettysburg Times, Feb 1)]</ref>{{Rp|7}} and by June 26 hotels in Hanover, Chambersburg, Hagerstown, and "the Blue Ridge section [were] filling rapidly".<ref name=June26/> For entertainment, a Gettysburg facility was started in 1912 to display the Boston version of the [[Gettysburg Cyclorama]],[https://books.google.com/books?id=SdrYv7S60fgC&pg=PA542] and the now [[The Battle of Gettysburg (1913 film)|lost ''The Battle of Gettysburg'' black & white film of 1913]] was first run at Walter's Theatre on June 26.<ref name=June26>{{Cite news |date=June 26, 1913 |title=Walter's Theatre ….Here…. The Battle Of Gettysburg", "First Boys in Gray Here, & "Many Cancel Reservations |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=B6VcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6548,1961459&dq=wizard-theatre+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archive |newspaper=Gettysburg Times |publisher=Times and News Publishing Company |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref> Local planning for the reunion included expanding the Gettysburg hackman's tax to automobiles [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=waRcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6534,179391&dq=hackmen+gettysburg&hl=en] (upheld by the Pennsylvania Supreme Court in 1914), a 50 cent maximum for taxi fares in the borough,[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=66RcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6960,1224251&dq=hackmen+gettysburg&hl=en] and an obscure request from a few Missouri veterans regarding the availability near Gettysburg of "a few good widows or old maids … good housekeepers and not too young" to go west after the reunion (the "kind-hearted mayor", J. A. Holtzworth, agreed to forward photos to the veterans in the "Cupid … operations")!<ref name=June2>{{Cite news |date=June 2, 1913 |title=Chance for Local Husband Hunters |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=86RcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6562,1446241&dq=missouri+gettysburg+burgess+mayor+1913&hl=en |format=Google News Archives |newspaper=Gettysburg Times |publisher=Times and News Publishing Company |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref>
==Facilities== [[File:Reu13gc.jpeg|right|thumb|375px|Great Camp on the [[Gettysburg Battlefield]].]] The War Department's '''Great Camp'''<!--Beitler p. 40--> (Gettysburg Encampment,<!--Beitler p. 71--> Anniversary Camp,<!--Beitler p. 87--> Veterans Camp<!--Beitler p. 91-->)<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|40,71,87,91}} provided tents and support facilities for the Civil War veterans and extended from both sides of [[Long Lane, Gettysburg|Long Lane]] on the north [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1913/06/29/100271968.pdf] to within 500 yards of the Bliss House.<ref>{{Cite news |date=July 3, 1913 |title=Veteran's Joyful Over Camp's End |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=S0kiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rnQFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2009,237140&dq=the-angle+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archives |location=[[New London, Connecticut]] |newspaper=The Day |accessdate=2011-02-02}}</ref> The Great Camp included the Great Tent (Big Tent,<!--ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|75}}--> 200 x 450&nbsp;ft)<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} "with its thirteen thousand chairs";<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|94}}--> the veterans' tents; quarters for 1,466 War Department soldiers (including camp commander Gen. Liggitt) & 2,179 mess personnel<!-- cooks, kitchen helpers, bakers, and laborers -->; 385 camp Boy Scouts from Washington;<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|49}}--> and other camp personnel for a total of 57,198 "''persons quartered and subsisted in the Great Camp''".<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|40}} The camp had a temporary U. S. Post Office;<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|84b}} 90 Pennsylvania Health Department latrines throughout the camp with a seating capacity of 3,476;<ref name=Bradley/>{{Rp|58}} and near the Great Tent, an Emergency Station and 2 Comfort Houses of the health dept, which also supplied the Great Tent water fountains.<ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|75}} The Pennsylvania commission also set up a temporary morgue in the camp.<ref name=Bradley/>{{Rp|56}} A special platform on the [[Round Top Branch]] was built for veterans to disembark from steamtrains directly into the camp<ref name=June28>{{Cite news |date=June 28, 1913 |title=Expecting Many More Veterans & Railroad Telephone |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9jdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YjoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6267,1899177&dq=president-wilson+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archives |newspaper=Adams County News |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref> (in February, trolleys of the [[Gettysburg Electric Railway]] had been prohibited from using the branch).<ref name=Feb8/>
After the state health department's Chief Engineer had estimated Gettysburg (pop. 4,500) would be inundated with 100,000 people, <!--Beitler p. 54--> the borough agreed to the Commissioner of Health's request for his department to take over medical and sanitation efforts in the area from June 25-July 25.<ref name=Dixon>{{Cite report |last=Dixon |first=Samuel G |date=December 15, 1913 |title=Commissioner's Report |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=swkTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA72 |format=Google Books |work=Report of the Pennsylvania Commission |publisher=Pennsylvania Department of Health |accessdate=2011-02-06}}</ref>{{Rp|75}} The department set up a field hospital at the Kurtz property facing Brickyard Lane on the north foot of East [[Cemetery Hill]], as well as 6 Comfort Stations in the borough (1 at each [[Gettysburg Railroad Station|railroad station]]), with a total of ~100 hoppers.{{Clarify|date=June 2013}}<ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|82}} The department also tested borough wells and mitigated contamination sources upstream of the [[Sachs Covered Bridge|Water Works supply]] on [[Marsh Creek (Monocacy River)|Marsh Creek]]. The American Red Cross Society, along with 72 additional Boy Scouts<!--ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|51}}--> operated fourteen 7&nbsp;ft x 7&nbsp;ft<!--ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|86}}--> Relief Stations for first aid and rest on the battlefield park roads,<ref name=Bradley/>{{Rp|55}} and the Tuberculosis Dispensary in Gettysburg was also used as a Relief Station.<ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|86}}
Attached to the Great Camp were a battery of the Third United States Field Artillery and several companies of Regular Infantry.<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} Companies A-D (14 officers & 285 men)<ref name=Commission>{{Cite Gettysburg Commission Reports}} "''The United States land on the battlefield is used by the Quartermaster’s Department for camp site No. 1. Part of the farm (formerly Codori) of William F. Redding, lessee, approximately 28 acres, also tract (formerly Barrett heirs) and part of the farm (formerly McMillan), both properties rented to the Quartermaster Corps, U.S.A., by O. D. McMillan, 56 acres; a total of 84 acres.''" (1913 report) "''The Pennsylvania Commission, a congressional committee, and State representatives, composing a joint commission. They have had various meetings as the work developed. The first meeting was held in Gettysburg at the courthouse October 13, 1910, noted in the annual report for 1911. There were other meetings held elsewhere. A meeting was held at Gettysburg December 13, 1912, at Hotel Gettysburg. The next meeting was held at the Union League, Philadelphia, January 23, 24, and 25, 1913. … This great project, which was inaugurated September 8, 1908, by the chairman of the Gettysburg National Park Commission''" (after the April 1908 idea of General [[Henry S. Huidekoper]])</ref> of the [[15th Cavalry Division (United States)|Fifteenth United States Cavalry]] arrived on June 26 for guarding the battlefield<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'13}} and camped west of [[Seminary Ridge]] on the Hagerstown Rd,<ref name=June28/> while a "model Camp" for a Pennsylvania cavalry squadron was on the "College Athletic Field" adjoining the Commission's Headquarters.<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|52}} A total of 527 people were quartered at both the [[Lutheran Theological Seminary at Gettysburg]] & the [[Gettysburg College|Pennsylvania College ("Gettysburg College" in 1921<!-- http://activerain.com/blogsview/1429716/gettysburg-college-a-vibrant-neighborhood-within-gettysburg-pa -->)]], including the Pennsylvania Gettysburg Commission, 4 troops of Pennsylvania State Police, and in tents, Governor Tener's staff.<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|49}} Additional nearby encampments included the leased Newspaper Row ("Meadeboro") with 155 journalists north of the [[Gettysburg National Cemetery]],<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|40}} an encampment of 30 Boy Scouts near [[Cashtown, Pennsylvania|Cashtown]] west of Gettysburg for traveler services<ref name=June7>{{Cite news |date=June 7, 1913 |title=Many Students Will Be Here|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_b9cAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rVgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1011,6646691&dq=newspaper-row+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archive |newspaper=Adams County News |accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref>{{Rp|5}} on the Chambersburg-Gettysburg Pike, and Philadelphia and Baltimore salvation army encamped in Stonesifer's Grove at [[Biglerville, Pennsylvania]].[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JlYzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CPMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2540,3049345&dq=pathe-weekly+gettysburg&hl=en]
[[File:Reu13ff.jpeg|350px|thumb|right|For the Webb/Pickett flag ceremony, two 1863 units advanced about {{Convert |50|ft|m|abbr=on}}—Union from the North, Confederate from the South—to flags at [[The Angle]] stone wall where they "clasped hands and buried their faces on each other's shoulders".<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|167–8,171s}}]]
==Events== The Great Camp opened for supper on June 29 with [[Gettysburg Battlefield camps after the American Civil War|Pennsylvania veterans from the state reunion that adjourned on June 28]] and other early veterans (e.g. 2 Confederate vets of [[Culp's Hill]] had arrived on June 26).<ref name=June26/> The 21,000 arrivals on the 29th instead of the 6,000<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|52}} expected by Capt McCaskey of the Quartermasters Corps<ref name=June28/> resulted in initial shortages (some veterans left without staying). After the 1912 [http://www.gdg.org/Research/Authored%20Items/BCRReports/1916.html] base of the [[Virginia Monument]] was dedicated on June 30,<ref name=Pittsburgh>{{Cite news |date=July 1, 1913 |title=Pathetic Night Scene in Veterans' Great Reunion |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=TEQbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IEkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4129,23763&dq=gettysburg+high-water-mark&hl=en |format=Google News Archive |newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press |accessdate=2011-02-28 |quote=''Yesterday afternoon … the dedication of the Lee uncompleted ''[Virginia]'' monument took place.''}} '''NOTE''': A violent event away from the reunion was [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DKVcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6769,2116754&dq=andrew-cowan+gettysburg&hl=en at Hotel Gettysburg where a man used a "vile epithet" for President Lincoln and stabbed 8 people] [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9jdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YjoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6389,1940348&dq=wilson-here+for-one-hour&hl=en The VA governor subsequently spoke on behalf of the perpetrator, a Philadelphia attorney in the area to locate his father that he claimed was a Confederate general. The father, a Confederate Major posted the bail.]</ref> official reunion events began on July 1, '''Veteran's Day''', and included a speech by [[John Wanamaker]].[http://williamzulker.com/john_wanamaker]
;July 2: '''Military Day''' included an address recommending a stronger military ("we ought to build two battleships for every one laid down by Japan"), a reading of the [[Gettysburg Address]], and a [[Seminary Ridge]] review of the VA division by their governor.<ref name=July3/> At night, an impromptu Union raid on the Confederate side of the Great Camp resulted in joint parades and camp fires following the "charge".<ref name=July3>{{Cite news |date=July 3, 1913 |title=March on Rebs: Blues Advanced on the Grays Wednesday Night", "Many Leaving", "Reviewed Virginians |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DKVcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6769,2116754&dq=andrew-cowan+gettysburg&hl=en |format=Google News Archives |newspaper=Gettysburg Times |publisher=Times and News Publishing Company |accessdate=2011-02-08}}</ref>
;July 3: '''Civic/Governors' Day''' had 65 unit reunions,<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|133}} the [[William Wells (general)|Wells statue]] dedication,<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} and a [[:Wikisource:1913 Gettysburg reunion flag ceremony|Webb/Pickett flag ceremony]] at the [[The Angle|Bloody Angle]] on the hour of [[Pickett's Charge]].<ref name=Beitler>{{Cite report |last=Beitler |first=Lewis Eugene (editor and compiler) |date=December 31, 1913 |title=Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg: Report of the Pennsylvania Commission |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=swkTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA168 |format=Google Books |location=[[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]] |publisher=Wm. Stanley Bay (state printer)<!-- p. -i -->|accessdate=2011-02-06 }} </ref> In the Great Tent from 4:30-6 P.M. was the New York Veterans' Celebration, which included a speech by Colonel Andrew Cowan in which he again called for a [[Eternal Light Peace Memorial|Gettysburg peace memorial]].<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|153–65}} The fireworks by the Pain Fireworks Display Company [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-qRcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6527,1616341&dq=sedgwick+round-top+gettysburg&hl=en] at 9 p.m. included "gigantic set pieces covering the entire face and crest of Little Round Top".<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|171}}
;July 4: On '''National Day''', [[the Pennsylvania State Memorial]] with 8 statues installed in April [http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:PAmonument-Gettysburg.JPG was dedicated], and [[President of the United States|President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]] arrived at 11 a.m. in a special train car, traveled through the borough, and entered the Great Tent through 2 rows of Boy Scouts. Wilson addressed the audience in the Big Tent about national unity and departed the camp after the National Anthem that followed (attendees similarly returned to their quarters). The subsequent Tribute to Our Heroic Dead with "a silent, solemn, sacred five minutes at 'Attention' by" people throughout the Gettysburg area, e.g., at the "College Hotel" & "Seminary Hotel". The Tribute began with a bugle salute over the camp while the Gettysburg bells tolled noon in the distance, followed by the remaining minutes of silence punctuated by periodic artillery firing from the distance. From 5 a.m. to 11 p.m., 7,147 automobiles (at least 1 from each state) used the national park roads.<ref name=Commission/>
Departures included 12,000 veterans on July 2 and about the same number on July 3,<ref name=July3/> and dismantling of the Great Camp began immediately after the July 4 Tribute. The hospital closed on July 5,<!--ref name=Dixon/>{{Rp|83}}--> and the last veteran left on July 8. The [[Gettysburg Battlefield camps after the American Civil War|annual military instructional camp]] (250 college students)[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DqVcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ZlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=7049,2164405&dq=hackmen+gettysburg&hl=en] used a few tents of the veterans camp<ref name=Commission/>{{Rp|'14}} while encamped at the "Meadeboro" camp (Newspaper Row) from July 7-August 15.[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_b9cAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rVgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1011,6646691&dq=newspaper-row+gettysburg&hl=en] The Quartermaster headquarters on Baltimore St closed on August 13, and by August 15 the entire Grand Camp had been removed except "four great water storage reservoirs". A movie, ''United at Gettysburg'', documented the reunion,[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zcxJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-IQMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5136,1059610&dq=pathe-weekly+gettysburg&hl=en] and Lt Col Lewis E. Beitler, Secretary of the Commission, completed the compilation of the organizations' reports on the December 31, 1913.<ref name=Beitler/>{{Rp|178}}
To commemorate the 1913 Gettysburg reunion, a colonial portico was opened in May 1914 at the Seminary's Old Dorm [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=DzhUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YjoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6392,3948778&dq=hackmen+gettysburg&hl=en] (only the concrete base remains),[https://books.google.com/books?id=rFHr8ti5sAwC&pg=PA164] and the 1938 [[Eternal Light Peace Memorial]] was erected on [[Oak Ridge, Adams County, Pennsylvania|Oak Ridge]], north of Gettysburg. {{For|the 75th battle anniversary that President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] addressed|1938 Gettysburg reunion}}
{{Quote box |align=right |width=30em |fontsize=85% |title=Reunion names in the official report |quote=The Congressional committee used the name '''Celebration of the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg''',<!--p. 167--> but other organizations and officials used numerous other names: <br>{{·}} Celebration of the Semi-Centenary of the Civil War <br>{{·}} Gettysburg Celebration<!--p. 220--> {{·}} Reunion Celebration at Gettysburg<!--pp. 46,211--> <br>{{·}} Gettysburg Reunion {{·}} Gettysburg Peace Reunion <br>{{·}} Great Peace Reunion {{·}} Great Peace Jubilee {{·}} Golden Jubilee <br>{{·}} Great Reunion {{·}} Grand Reunion {{·}} Blue and Gray Reunion <br>and in a souvenir program of poems: '''Grand Reunion of the Blue and the Gray on the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg'''<ref name=Crawford/> }}
