'''Behavior imaging''' is a technique used in [[behavioral health]] to diagnose, treat and monitor [[Emotional and behavioral disorders|behavioral disorders]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Oberleitner|first=Ron|author2=Patt Elison-Bowers|author3=Uwe Reischl|author4=Jim Ball|title=Optimizing the Personal Health Record with Special Video Capture for the Treatment of Autism|journal=Journal of Developmental and Physical Disabilities|date=October 2007|volume=19|issue=5|pages=513–518|doi=10.1007/s10882-007-9067-3|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10882-007-9067-3}}</ref> most commonly [[autism]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Oberleitner|first=Ron|author2=Rebecca Wurtz|author3=Michael L. Popovich|author4=Reno Fiedler|author5=Tim Moncher|author6=Swamy Laxminarayan|author7=Uwe Reischl|title=Behavior Imaging's Assessment Technology: A Mobile Infrastructure to Transform Autism Diagnosis and Treatment|journal=Future Visions on Biomedicine and Bioinformatics|year=2011|volume=2|series=Communications in Medical and Care Compunetics|pages=1–8|doi=10.1007/8754_2010_10|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/8754_2010_10}}</ref> It involves capturing short video clips of problem behaviors in natural environments on smartphones or other devices.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Eugene|title=App aims for faster autism diagnosis|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/04/13/autism-application-faster-diagnosis/2080247/|accessdate=11/8/13|newspaper=USA Today|date=4/3/13}}</ref>

