{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}
[[Image:Sri Lankan woman and child.jpg|Sri Lankan woman and child|thumb]]
{{Women in society sidebar}}
All [[ethnic groups in Sri Lanka]] have many distinctions regarding the '''roles of the sexes'''.
[[Sri Lanka]] was the first nation in the world to elect a female head of state, [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]. Bandaranaike won the election in 1960 after [[S. W. R. D. Bandaranaike|S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike]], the preceding leader who was also her husband, was murdered by a spy.

While Sri Lanka relatively excels when it comes to gender equality indices, there are still many underlying issues pertaining to [[Gender Inequality in Sri Lanka|gender inequality in Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gender Inequality Index (GII) {{!}} Human Development Reports|url = http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/gender-inequality-index-gii|website = hdr.undp.org|accessdate = 2015-10-22}}</ref>

Many '''[[Women in Sri Lanka]]''' choose to work, while some choose to work at home and care for children. In families relying on [[agriculture]], women are in charge of [[weeding]] and help with the [[harvest]]. Among poor families, women also perform full-time work for upper class individuals. Moreover, the man's role used to be seen as providing his family with [[material support]] by looking after his business. 

At the center of the hierarchy are children, who mix freely and receive a great deal of [[affection]] from both sexes. Among the middle- and upper-income classes, education of children may last into their early twenties, and women may mix with males or even take on jobs that were in the past reserved for men. For poorer income children, they may go to work at an earlier age.

==Gender inequality==
{{Main|Gender inequality in Sri Lanka}}
In comparison to other countries in the region, Sri Lanka is ranked well on several [[Gender inequality|gender equality]] indices. However, there are also some sources that question the validity of these indices.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Towards a Fresh Start in Measuring Gender Equality: A Contribution to the Debate|url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/14649880600768660|journal = Journal of Human Development|date = 1 July 2006|issn = 1464-9888|pages = 275–283|volume = 7|issue = 2|doi = 10.1080/14649880600768660|first = A. Geske|last = Dijkstra}}</ref> Furthermore, globally, Sri Lanka ranks relatively low on gender equality indices.<ref>{{Cite web|title = United Nations Statistics Division - Demographic and Social Statistics|url = http://unstats.un.org/unsd/demographic/products/indwm/default.htm|website = unstats.un.org|accessdate = 9 October 2015}}</ref>  Overall, this pattern of social history that disempowers females produces a cycle of undervaluing females, providing only secondary access to health care and schooling and thus less opportunities to take on high-level jobs or training. In a study by Dr. Elaine Enarson, this cycle in turn worsens the issue of low political participation and social rights.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Gender and natural disasters|url = http://www.ilo.org/employment/Whatwedo/Publications/WCMS_116391/lang--en/index.htm|website = www.ilo.org|date = 1 September 2000|accessdate = 2 November 2015|first = Elaine Enarson, Crisis Response and Reconstruction,|last = ILO}}</ref>

