{{Infobox criminal | name = Myles Fukunaga | image_name = | image_size = | image_caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1909|02|04}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1929|11|19|1909|02|04}} | death_place = [[O'ahu]] | alias = | conviction = [[Murder]] (September 18, 1928) | conviction_penalty = Death by hanging | conviction_status = [[Execution|Executed]] | occupation = [[Hospitality industry|Hotel worker]] | spouse = | parents = | children = }}
'''Myles Yukata Fukunaga''' was a Japanese-American from Honolulu, Hawaii. In 1928, he kidnapped and murdered George Gill Jamieson, the 10-year-old son of a local banker.
Subsequent to the murder, he demanded a $10,000 ransom. Before the body of the victim was found, the Hawaiian Trust Company offered a reward of $5,000 with no questions asked.<ref name=honosearch>{{cite news |title=All Honolulu on Search to Find Son of Banker|newspaper=Schenectady Gazette |date=Sep 20, 1928 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dmMhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jIYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3582,2396636&dq=gill-jamieson+ransom }}</ref> Fukunaga eventually received $4,000 in $5 bills from the victim's father before he was arrested.<ref name=slayboy>{{cite news |title=Kidnappers Slay Boy|newspaper=The Pittsburgh Press|date=Sep 21, 1928 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Cu8aAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OEoEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1677,3671800&dq=ransom+gill-jamieson }}</ref>
